A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric alcove, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are broken up fish mills.
This is Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
In the night the whole facade looks even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same winding lines and intertwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even bellholes and ledges.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district at the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, executed by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally stood on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but he finally agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the house Casa Batlló did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative home of the real owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were the result of his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Güell Park, in which other works of Antoni Gaudí are located.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of his organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "stairing house".
It is also said that on top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the Patron of Catalonia.
But other figurative elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilating channels and typical fireplaces for the house for the time.
A little bit bizarre already mutates her 45-degree slope.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and was not allowed to get away from them.
Before the construction began, he received from the city the corresponding building permit, but the information he had provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when the city fathers were finished, they were so horrified by the result that they demanded remedial action.
The councillors also insisted, among other things, on the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, however, only fifteen days after the call of the district, Josep Batlló made an application to approve the renting of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
On the second floor of the gallery there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be connected completely by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors, apart from a new facade, by Gaudí's reconstruction.
It is also impressive Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts.
The play of these two colours gives a high level of light to all floors of the house.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
House Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The landlords decided not to take this step until the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a quite inclusive business, the visits were kept, yes, they were extended to other common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the building monument is not a cardboard bar, it is 16.50 Euro, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the admission prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
