During the period 1994-2009, with her colleagues in Britain, she persecuted more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the pointing finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer, as for 19 percent of those men whose ring fingers and toe fingers were the same length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, even by 87 percent in men.
