Sports and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
In the game of 23 November against the Ajax in the Champions League, the alleged exclusion of two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is widely known, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty during the next league against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the Ethos - the unwritten but in this sport-based rules.
Part of the debate on the case presented is the fact that a team of the football club Real Madrid (which presents in his anthemne of nobleness and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role, and the dramatisation by Mourinho, who added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether it expressly contradicts the principles of sports which are not expressly prohibited by the statutes, i.e. whether these acts constitute a regular bypass. In fact, this procedure adheres to the statutes of sports, but seems to be compromising its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused by the sports spirit should be examined.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect which was not threatened by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the unwarranted players from taking an unjust advantage from the counter-team. This also did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand as false play or rule, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and accepted the sanction joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed that the rival was neither put into a more unfavorable position nor raised benefits for the played game, because the obvious result of this action was that your team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also no useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually leave. In addition, the players will receive a sanction with this procedure and pass into the second card cycle in which they leave less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
This does not make it so clear whether it really is an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the sports spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule-over), they wanted to choose when to make it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the line between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics came about as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of provocated rule transfer.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than aesthetic.
